2026-04-03T10:40:25.596204Z  INFO session_loop{thread_id=019d5247-8044-7113-a227-a181e2c40e45}:submission_dispatch{otel.name="op.dispatch.user_input" submission.id="019d52e7-853f-7ad1-a67b-d780f8425919" codex.op="user_input"}:turn{otel.name="session_task.turn" thread.id=019d5247-8044-7113-a227-a181e2c40e45 turn.id=019d52e7-853f-7ad1-a67b-d780f8425919 model=gpt-5.4}: codex_core::stream_events_utils: ToolCall: exec_command {"cmd":"python3 - <<'PY'\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\nroot = Path('/Users/macbook/Documents/AI Dev Projects/Artwork Review Tool')\ndrafts = root / '.omx' / 'drafts'\ndrafts.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)\nts = datetime.now(timezone.utc).strftime('%Y-%m-%d')\nprd = drafts / f'prd-{ts}-revision-5-roles-permissions-draft.md'\ntest = drafts / f'test-spec-{ts}-revision-5-roles-permissions-draft.md'\nprd.write_text('''# PRD Draft — Revision 5 Roles & Permissions\n\n## Metadata\n- **Date:** 2026-04-03\n- **Mode:** `$plan --consensus --direct` in deliberate RALPLAN-DR mode\n- **Primary source:** `.omx/specs/deep-interview-revision-5-roles-permissions.md:24-145`\n- **Scope:** Brownfield Next.js + Supabase authorization upgrade for Nexus purchase-order and artwork workflows\n\n## Requirements Summary\nImplement a real permissions system so the wrong people cannot edit the wrong things, irrelevant actions are hidden, and vendor/designer responsibilities stay separated. The agreed scope requires end-to-end enforcement in UI and server actions, additive functional roles (Purchaser, Designer, Vendor), org-scoped Admin management, live refresh after permission changes, migration of existing `admin` users to Admin, and no Super Admin/custom role builder/audit/RLS redesign (`.omx/specs/deep-interview-revision-5-roles-permissions.md:27-77`).\n\n## Current-State Evidence\n1. The app still models authorization as a binary `UserRole = 'user' | 'admin'` and stores it directly on the `User` record (`nexus/src/types/database.ts:1-16`).\n2. The original schema only defines `user_role AS ENUM ('user', 'admin')` and stores it on `users.role`; RLS remains broad and is explicitly out of scope to redesign (`nexus/supabase/migrations/001_initial_schema.sql:8-28,85-149`).\n3. Admin page access is hard-coded to `user.role === 'admin'`, and the page currently just loads all users plus password-change support (`nexus/src/app/(protected)/admin/page.tsx:15-64`).\n4. `getAllUsers()` currently returns every user in the table with no organization filter, which conflicts with the requirement that Admin manages users in their organization (`nexus/src/app/actions/users.ts:29-38`).\n5. `UserList` currently displays only a single role chip and a Change Password action; there is no roles/permissions editor (`nexus/src/components/admin/UserList.tsx:66-194`).\n6. The protected shell shows the Admin Panel link only when `user.role === 'admin'` (`nexus/src/components/layout/Header.tsx:154-167`).\n7. Orders page currently allows any authenticated org-scoped user to create orders, because the create button is always rendered and `createOrder()` only checks auth/org membership, not permissions (`nexus/src/app/(protected)/orders/page.tsx:204-227`; `nexus/src/app/actions/orders.ts:62-82`).\n8. Order editing controls are all interactive today: date changes, order archive/delete, add item, per-item priority/status/item/category/qty/version/approval/art/notes/delete (`nexus/src/components/orders/OrderBlock.tsx:194-227,245-360`; `nexus/src/components/orders/OrderItemRow.tsx:257-373`).\n9. Artwork modal and upload cards still reduce authorization to a boolean `isAdmin`; upload delete is server-enforced as admin-only, but status/notes/archive are available to any org member (`nexus/src/components/orders/ArtworkModal.tsx:161-170,223-234`; `nexus/src/components/uploads/UploadSessionCard.tsx:139-182`; `nexus/src/app/actions/uploads.ts:132-217`).\n10. Item/category/item-name/product-line mutations are org-scoped but not permission-scoped, so any org member can currently mutate them (`nexus/src/app/actions/items.ts:54-159`; `nexus/src/app/actions/categories.ts:35-110`; `nexus/src/app/actions/itemNames.ts:33-86`; `nexus/src/app/actions/productLines.ts:33-70`).\n11. The protected shell already wraps all pages in a client `AppShell`, and orders page already uses Supabase Realtime subscriptions for status refreshes; these are good integration points for live permission refresh (`nexus/src/components/layout/AppShell.tsx:15-30`; `nexus/src/app/(protected)/orders/page.tsx:112-137`).\n12. Self-service registration currently creates a user with display name/email/password only; org assignment happens later, which matches the clarified requirement that Admin assigns new users to an organization (`nexus/src/app/(auth)/register/page.tsx:22-57`).\n\n## RALPLAN-DR Summary\n### Principles\n1. Keep the permission source of truth centralized so UI and server actions resolve the same effective access.\n2. Prefer the smallest brownfield schema change that still supports additive roles, overrides, and live refresh.\n3. Preserve org isolation and current Admin behavior while expanding non-admin role granularity.\n4. Make permission rules testable at the action level, not just visually hidden in the UI.\n5. Reuse existing Supabase Realtime patterns instead of introducing a separate event system.\n\n### Decision Drivers\n1. **End-to-end enforcement:** server actions must stop relying on org membership alone.\n2. **Brownfield speed:** Revision 5 excludes custom role builder and RLS redesign, so complexity should stay app-layer-focused.\n3. **Live update UX:** permission changes must invalidate affected user sessions/pages quickly without forcing hard logout semantics.\n\n### Viable Options\n#### Option A — Permission document on `users` + shared resolver (**favored**)\n**Approach:** Keep `users.role` for `user/admin`, add structured functional-role + override data plus a permissions version/timestamp on `users`, and resolve effective permissions via a shared library consumed by UI and server actions.\n- **Pros:** Minimal migration surface; single-row realtime subscription for live refresh; easy to preserve existing admin semantics; supports additive roles and per-permission overrides without many joins.\n- **Cons:** Lower relational strictness; requires strong runtime validation/types; mutation payloads can become bulky if the permission schema sprawls.\n\n#### Option B — Normalized role-assignment + override tables\n**Approach:** Keep `users.role` for baseline role, add tables such as `user_functional_roles` and `user_permission_overrides`, and resolve effective permissions from relational rows.\n- **Pros:** Stronger database integrity; clearer auditability later; cleaner SQL introspection for future reporting.\n- **Cons:** More migrations, more joins, more complex live-refresh fan-out, and a larger brownfield change for a revision that explicitly avoids custom role management scope.\n\n#### Invalidated alternative — Per-capability columns on `users`\nA wide-column approach was rejected because the role matrix already needs mixed booleans and levelled permissions (Designer disabled/view/edit), and the prompt requires editable role templates plus individual overrides. This would create a brittle schema with poor extensibility.\n\n### Chosen Direction\nChoose **Option A**: retain `users.role` as the admin flag, add a typed permission document + monotonic `permissions_updated_at`/`permissions_version` signal on `users`, and introduce a shared permission resolver used everywhere.\n\n### Pre-mortem (3 scenarios)\n1. **Permission drift:** UI hides a control but the matching server action still allows the mutation.  \n   **Mitigation:** every protected mutation routes through a shared `requirePermission()` helper; test spec pairs UI expectations with action-level assertions.\n2. **Live refresh noise or misses:** affected users do not refresh reliably, or all users refresh unnecessarily.  \n   **Mitigation:** subscribe only to the current user’s `users` row and compare `permissions_updated_at` / version before calling `router.refresh()`.\n3. **Migration confusion:** existing admins lose access or newly registered users get incorrect defaults/org assignment state.  \n   **Mitigation:** explicit migration defaults, backfill script, and regression checks for admin page access plus “no organization assigned” states.\n\n## ADR\n### Decision\nImplement a centralized permission resolver backed by a structured permission document on `users`, plus org-scoped admin management and realtime refresh on user-row permission updates.\n\n### Drivers\n- Directly matches the clarified spec’s additive roles, override editing, and live-refresh needs.\n- Minimizes migration and realtime complexity in an already shipping brownfield app.\n- Preserves current `admin` semantics while allowing granular non-admin permissions.\n\n### Alternatives considered\n- Normalized assignment/override tables\n- Wide per-capability columns on `users`\n\n### Why chosen\nOption A satisfies the revision’s functional requirements with the fewest moving parts: one canonical resolver, one row to query for live refresh, and one migration path for existing admins/users.\n\n### Consequences\n- Permission schema must be strongly typed and validated in application code.\n- Admin editing UI should write both role-template selections and explicit overrides into the structured document.\n- Future reporting/audit features may later require extracting some of this data into relational tables.\n\n### Follow-ups\n- Validate the final permission-document shape during implementation with shared TypeScript types and migration defaults.\n- Add explicit regression coverage around each protected action and the live refresh trigger.\n\n## Proposed Permission Model\n1. Keep `users.role` as `'user' | 'admin'` for baseline Admin capability and migration compatibility (`nexus/src/types/database.ts:1-16`; `nexus/supabase/migrations/001_initial_schema.sql:8-28`).\n2. Add a structured permission payload on `users` (or a one-to-one sidecar row if migration ergonomics require it) with:\n   - `functionalRoles`: `{ purchaser: boolean, vendor: boolean, designer: 'disabled' | 'view' | 'edit' }`\n   - `overrides`: atomic capability overrides for individual actions shown in the admin editor\n   - `permissionsUpdatedAt` (or incrementing version) for realtime refresh\n3. Define canonical role templates in code, not DB-configurable UI, because custom role builder is out of scope.\n4. Compute effective permissions via “admin full access” OR additive functional roles OR explicit overrides, with more-permissive wins.\n\n## Permission Matrix to Implement\n### Baseline\n- **Admin:** preserve current effective full access to existing workflows and add org-scoped user permission management.\n- **Default user:** authenticated org member with no special functional role access beyond non-protected page visibility already required by the product.\n\n### Purchaser capabilities\n- Create order\n- Change order date\n- Add order items\n- Edit item name/category/qty/notes/priority/order status\n- Delete order items\n- Archive order\n\n### Designer capabilities\n- `disabled`: hide version, artwork status, art button\n- `view`: show version + artwork status\n- `edit`: edit version, artwork status, and open artwork modal\n\n### Vendor capabilities\n- View priority, item order status, item name, category, qty, artwork version, artwork status, art button, notes\n- Open artwork uploads modal\n- Cannot edit qty/item name/category/version/priority/order status/artwork status\n- Cannot delete line items unless Purchaser capability is also present\n\n## Implementation Steps\n1. **Introduce typed permission schema + shared resolver**  \n   Files: `nexus/src/types/database.ts`, new `nexus/src/lib/auth/permissions.ts`, new `nexus/src/lib/auth/currentUserAccess.ts`.  \n   Work: add permission payload typing, template definitions, “more permissive wins” resolver, and helpers such as `canManageUsers`, `canCreateOrder`, `canEditDesignerFields`, `canDeleteUploadSession`.\n\n2. **Add schema/migration support and migrate existing users**  \n   Files: new migration after `nexus/supabase/migrations/013_add_purchase_order_archived.sql`, `nexus/src/types/database.ts`.  \n   Work: extend `users` with permission payload + refresh marker, backfill existing `admin` users to Admin/full access, leave existing `user` users with empty functional roles, and keep registration defaults compatible with later org assignment.\n\n3. **Harden user-management backend for org-scoped permission administration**  \n   Files: `nexus/src/app/actions/users.ts`, `nexus/src/app/(protected)/admin/page.tsx`.  \n   Work: scope user listing to current admin’s organization, add action(s) to update permissions and assign organization, and replace direct `role === 'admin'` checks with shared permission helpers.\n\n4. **Replace the current User Management table/modal with a Roles & Permissions editor**  \n   Files: `nexus/src/components/admin/UserList.tsx`, optional new `nexus/src/components/admin/*` subcomponents, `nexus/src/app/(protected)/admin/page.tsx`.  \n   Work: preserve password change, add edit affordance, expose whole-role toggles plus individual capability controls, and show effective role state clearly.\n\n5. **Add live permission refresh in the protected client shell**  \n   Files: `nexus/src/components/layout/AppShell.tsx`, `nexus/src/lib/supabase/client.ts`, optional new `nexus/src/hooks/usePermissionRefresh.ts`.  \n   Work: subscribe to the signed-in user’s `users` row, detect permission version/timestamp changes, and call `router.refresh()` so the current page re-renders under the new effective permissions.\n\n6. **Gate navigation and admin entry points with the shared resolver**  \n   Files: `nexus/src/components/layout/Header.tsx`, `nexus/src/components/layout/AppNav.tsx`, `nexus/src/app/(protected)/layout.tsx`.  \n   Work: stop showing irrelevant admin/system actions when the effective permission set does not allow them; preserve allowed navigation for assigned roles.\n\n7. **Apply UI permission gating to orders and artwork workflows**  \n   Files: `nexus/src/app/(protected)/orders/page.tsx`, `nexus/src/components/orders/OrderBlock.tsx`, `nexus/src/components/orders/OrderItemRow.tsx`, `nexus/src/components/orders/ArtworkModal.tsx`, `nexus/src/components/uploads/UploadSessionCard.tsx`, `nexus/src/app/(protected)/artwork/page.tsx`.  \n   Work: hide/disable create-order, archive/delete, add-item, item-field editors, art button, artwork status, upload delete, and other prompt-defined affordances based on effective permissions.\n\n8. **Apply server-action enforcement to every protected mutation touched by the role matrix**  \n   Files: `nexus/src/app/actions/orders.ts`, `nexus/src/app/actions/uploads.ts`, `nexus/src/app/actions/items.ts`, `nexus/src/app/actions/categories.ts`, `nexus/src/app/actions/itemNames.ts`, `nexus/src/app/actions/productLines.ts` (and any newly added admin permission actions).  \n   Work: replace org-only checks with org + permission checks so hidden controls are backed by action-level enforcement after refresh.\n\n9. **Verify migration, live refresh, and role-specific workflows end to end**  \n   Files: test artifacts from `.omx/plans/test-spec-2026-04-03-revision-5-roles-permissions.md`, plus lint/build scripts in `nexus/package.json:5-8`.  \n   Work: execute the test matrix, confirm user refresh behavior, and ensure existing admin accounts still work after migration.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n1. Existing admins retain effective full access after migration, and existing non-admin users start with no special functional roles.\n2. Admin sees only users in the same organization and can update their org assignment + permissions from User Management.\n3. Users with no applicable permission cannot see or trigger the protected order/artwork controls after page refresh.\n4. Purchaser-only users can perform purchaser actions but cannot use designer-only artwork-status/version editing unless separately granted.\n5. Designer `view` users can see version + artwork status but cannot edit them; Designer `edit` users can edit them and open the art modal.\n6. Vendor users can open the art modal and view the listed columns but cannot edit the forbidden fields; vendor + purchaser combined gets the more permissive result where they overlap.\n7. Deleting upload sessions and other destructive mutations are enforced server-side according to effective permissions, not just hidden in the UI.\n8. When an Admin updates a user’s permissions, the affected signed-in user’s current page refreshes automatically and newly forbidden controls disappear/work stops from that point forward.\n9. No Super Admin role, custom role builder, audit log, multi-org authorization redesign, or RLS redesign is introduced.\n\n## Risks and Mitigations\n- **Risk:** JSON/structured permission payload becomes inconsistent.  \n  **Mitigation:** central schema validator + migration default factory in `lib/auth/permissions.ts`.\n- **Risk:** Admin org scoping is bypassed in backend actions.  \n  **Mitigation:** derive current admin org once per action and filter all user-management queries by it.\n- **Risk:** UI gating causes layout churn or leaves empty columns.  \n  **Mitigation:** drive visibility from a shared column-capability map and test mixed role combinations.\n- **Risk:** Live refresh loops or spams.  \n  **Mitigation:** compare old/new permission version before `router.refresh()` and unsubscribe cleanly on unmount.\n- **Risk:** Missing touchpoints outside orders/artwork/admin.  \n  **Mitigation:** grep for current `role === 'admin'` and all mutation entry points during implementation kickoff.\n\n## Verification Steps\n1. Run `npm run lint` in `nexus/`.\n2. Run `npm run build` in `nexus/` to catch typed permission-model regressions and route issues.\n3. Execute the role matrix in `.omx/plans/test-spec-2026-04-03-revision-5-roles-permissions.md` for Admin, baseline user, Purchaser, Designer(view), Designer(edit), Vendor, and Vendor+Purchaser.\n4. Manually verify live refresh by keeping a target user on `/orders` and `/artwork`, updating their permissions as Admin, and confirming the page refreshes with changed access.\n5. Verify migration defaults against seeded/existing admin and user accounts.\n\n## Expanded Test Plan\n- **Unit:** permission resolver merge logic; capability predicates; migration default factory; live-refresh change detector.\n- **Integration:** admin updates permission payload; server actions reject disallowed mutations; org-scoped user listing and assignment.\n- **E2E/manual browser:** admin edits permissions, target user refreshes on active page, mixed-role visibility/editability matrix across orders/artwork/admin.\n- **Observability/manual diagnostics:** console/log tracing for permission-refresh events and rejected server actions during testing.\n\n## Available-Agent-Types Roster\n- `architect` — architecture/tradeoff review\n- `executor` — primary implementation lane\n- `debugger` — fix permission regressions and live-refresh issues\n- `test-engineer` — matrix/test design and hardening\n- `verifier` — completion evidence / claim validation\n- `security-reviewer` — trust-boundary review for permission enforcement\n- `code-reviewer` / `critic` — final quality pass\n- `writer` — migration notes / admin usage docs\n- `explore` — fast repo lookup during execution\n\n## Follow-up Staffing Guidance\n### If using `$ralph`\n- **Primary owner:** `executor` (high) — implement migration, resolver, admin UI, and gating sequentially.\n- **Sidecar checks:** `security-reviewer` (medium) after backend enforcement lands; `test-engineer` (medium) before final verification; `verifier` (high) at the end.\n- **Why this lane:** the work crosses schema, actions, and UI, but a single persistent owner reduces permission-model drift.\n\n### If using `$team`\n- **Lane 1 — Schema/Auth Core:** `executor` (high) owns migration + permission resolver + shared helpers.\n- **Lane 2 — Admin UX:** `executor` (medium/high) owns admin page/UserList modal redesign.\n- **Lane 3 — Orders/Artwork Gating:** `executor` (medium/high) owns client gating across orders/artwork/upload components.\n- **Lane 4 — Verification:** `test-engineer` (medium) and `verifier` (high) own the role matrix + live-refresh proof.\n- **Lane 5 — Security sanity check:** `security-reviewer` (medium) reviews server enforcement before signoff.\n\n## Launch Hints\n### Ralph\n```text\n$ralph .omx/plans/prd-2026-04-03-revision-5-roles-permissions.md\n```\n\n### Team\n```text\n$team .omx/plans/prd-2026-04-03-revision-5-roles-permissions.md\n```\n\nEquivalent OMX CLI hint:\n```text\nomx team .omx/plans/prd-2026-04-03-revision-5-roles-permissions.md\n```\n\n## Team Verification Path\n- **Team proves before shutdown:** migration applies cleanly, shared resolver exists, admin UI can mutate permissions, orders/artwork/admin touchpoints consume effective permissions, and live refresh triggers for the target user row.\n- **Ralph/verifier proves after handoff:** lint/build pass, role matrix pass, existing-admin migration proof, mixed-role additive behavior proof, and regression evidence that forbidden server actions reject after refresh.\n\n## Draft Changelog\n- Initial deliberate consensus draft created from deep-interview spec + brownfield evidence.\n''')\n\ntest.write_text('''# Test Spec Draft — Revision 5 Roles & Permissions\n\n## Metadata\n- **Date:** 2026-04-03\n- **PRD draft:** `.omx/drafts/prd-2026-04-03-revision-5-roles-permissions-draft.md`\n- **Source spec:** `.omx/specs/deep-interview-revision-5-roles-permissions.md:61-105`\n\n## Test Strategy Summary\nBecause Revision 5 changes authorization behavior, migration defaults, and live refresh, verification must cover three layers together:\n1. **Resolver correctness** — additive roles, more-permissive wins, and designer access levels.\n2. **Enforcement correctness** — protected server actions reject disallowed operations after refreshed permissions.\n3. **Experience correctness** — UI visibility/editability and live refresh match the effective permission set.\n\n## Test Fixtures / Personas\n1. **Admin existing user** — migrated from legacy `role = 'admin'`.\n2. **Baseline user** — migrated from legacy `role = 'user'`, no functional roles.\n3. **Purchaser user**\n4. **Designer view user**\n5. **Designer edit user**\n6. **Vendor user**\n7. **Vendor + Purchaser user**\n8. **Target user being edited live by Admin**\n9. **User without organization assignment**\n\n## Unit Tests\n### Permission resolver\n- Admin baseline resolves to full access.\n- Baseline user resolves to no special functional permissions.\n- Purchaser grants order creation/date/item-edit/delete/archive capabilities.\n- Designer `disabled/view/edit` resolves to the correct visibility + mutability for version/artwork controls.\n- Vendor grants view/open-art-modal permissions without forbidden field edits.\n- Vendor + Purchaser resolves with more-permissive wins on shared capabilities.\n- Explicit overrides can widen or narrow an individual capability as designed by the chosen schema.\n- `permissionsUpdatedAt` / version change detector only triggers refresh on actual changes.\n\n### Migration default factory\n- Legacy `admin` record backfills to Admin/full-access-compatible permission document.\n- Legacy `user` record backfills to empty functional-role document.\n- New registration default produces no organization + no functional roles.\n\n## Integration Tests\n### User management backend\n- `getAllUsers` replacement returns only users in the admin’s organization.\n- Non-admin caller cannot update another user’s permissions.\n- Admin can assign organization to an unassigned user in their org scope.\n- Permission update writes the refresh marker/version.\n\n### Protected server actions\nFor each protected action, test both allowed and denied paths after resolver integration:\n- `createOrder` (`nexus/src/app/actions/orders.ts:62-82`)\n- `updateOrderDate` (`nexus/src/app/actions/orders.ts:84-95`)\n- `createOrderItem` (`nexus/src/app/actions/orders.ts:127-162`)\n- `updateOrderItem` (`nexus/src/app/actions/orders.ts:164-199`)\n- `deleteOrderItem` (`nexus/src/app/actions/orders.ts:201-221`)\n- `archiveOrder` / `deleteOrder` (`nexus/src/app/actions/orders.ts:97-125`)\n- `updateUploadSessionStatus`, `updateUploadSessionNotes`, `archiveUploadSession`, `deleteUploadSession` (`nexus/src/app/actions/uploads.ts:132-217`)\n- `createItem`, `updateItem`, `deleteItem` (`nexus/src/app/actions/items.ts:54-159`)\n- Any new admin permission mutation action added in `users.ts`\n\n## End-to-End / Manual Browser Matrix\n### Admin\n- Can open Admin Panel.\n- Sees only users in same organization.\n- Can open user editor, toggle roles, edit underlying permissions, save successfully.\n- Existing password-change behavior still works.\n\n### Baseline user\n- Cannot access Admin Panel.\n- Cannot create orders or mutate order-item controls.\n- Does not see designer/vendor/purchaser-only affordances after refresh.\n\n### Purchaser\n- Can create order, change order date, add items, edit permitted fields, delete items, archive order.\n- Does not gain designer-only artwork-status/version editing unless also assigned Designer edit.\n\n### Designer view\n- Sees Version + Artwork Status.\n- Cannot edit Version or Artwork Status.\n- Art button behavior matches final implementation choice (hidden or non-interactive unless Designer edit / Vendor / Admin).\n\n### Designer edit\n- Can edit Version and Artwork Status.\n- Can open Artwork modal.\n\n### Vendor\n- Sees priority, order status, item name, category, qty, artwork version/status, art button, notes.\n- Cannot edit forbidden fields.\n- Can open Artwork modal.\n- Cannot delete line items.\n\n### Vendor + Purchaser\n- Inherits Vendor visibility plus Purchaser edit/delete/order-management rights where overlapping.\n- More-permissive rule confirmed on any conflicting capability.\n\n### Live refresh\n- Keep target user open on `/orders`; Admin changes permissions; target page refreshes and controls update.\n- Repeat on `/artwork`.\n- Verify no hard logout is required.\n- Verify changes take effect from refresh forward; no requirement to retroactively fail an action before refresh.\n\n### No-organization state\n- Newly registered/unassigned user still sees the existing “No organization assigned” guard until Admin assigns an org (`nexus/src/app/(protected)/orders/page.tsx:190-200`).\n\n## Verification Commands\nFrom `nexus/`:\n```bash\nnpm run lint\nnpm run build\n```\n\n## Exit Criteria\n- All resolver unit scenarios pass.\n- All protected-action allowed/denied integration scenarios pass.\n- Manual/e2e role matrix passes for every persona above.\n- Live refresh is observed on both `/orders` and `/artwork`.\n- Existing admin migration + baseline user migration behaviors are confirmed.\n- No Super Admin/custom role builder/audit/RLS redesign artifacts appear.\n\n## Open Verification Risks\n- No automated test runner is currently configured in `nexus/package.json:5-8`, so some integration/e2e coverage may need to start as manual QA or newly added tests during implementation.\n- Because RLS redesign is out of scope, verification must focus on app-layer server actions rather than database-level policy enforcement.\n''')\nprint(prd)\nprint(test)\nPY","workdir":"/Users/macbook/Documents/AI Dev Projects/Artwork Review Tool","yield_time_ms":1000,"max_output_tokens":4000} thread_id=019d5247-8044-7113-a227-a181e2c40e45
